  "prompt": "What is a good substitute for chipotle powder?",
  "response": "If you need a substitute for chipotle powder, there are several options depending on the flavor profile and heat level you prefer:\n\n1. **Smoked Paprika**: This is a great substitute if you want a similar smoky flavor without the heat. You might want to add a pinch of cayenne or red pepper flakes if you need some spice.\n\n2. **Cayenne Pepper**: If you want to maintain the heat but lose the smokiness, cayenne pepper can work well. Start with a smaller amount and adjust to taste.\n\n3. **Ancho Chili Powder**: This offers a mild heat and a slightly sweet flavor. It lacks the smokiness, so you can add a touch of smoked paprika to mimic that.\n\n4. **Regular Chili Powder**: While it lacks the specific smoky and spicy notes, it can be used in a pinch. You might want to balance it with a smoked seasoning or a bit of hot sauce.\n\n5. **Sriracha or Chipotle Sauce**: If you're cooking with liquids, these can provide a similar flavor and heat, but adjust the quantity based on the dish.\n\n6. **Homemade Blend**: If you have dried jalape\u00f1os or other peppers, you can grind them to create your own powder, adding smoked paprika to mimic the chipotle flavor.\n\nAdjust the quantity to suit your taste and the specific recipe you're working with!",
